article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw's late-game heroics lifted the Sparks to the brink of making the WNBA playoffs.
article.headline: Sparks keep playoff hopes alive with win
article.linkText: Holdsclaw lifts Sparks to brink of playoffs
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw made the moves that kept
the Los Angeles Sparks a viable contender in the WNBA.

Holdsclaw hit a 16-foot shot with 14.5 seconds remaining -- she
also blocked a shot and picked up a loose ball in the final 40
seconds -- as the Sparks defeated the San Antonio Silver Stars 70-67
Friday night.

The victory put Los Angeles (17-16) one game ahead of Phoenix
for fourth place in the West. The Sparks will advance to the
playoffs for the seventh consecutive season if they win at Houston
on Saturday or if Phoenix loses at defending champion Seattle on
Sunday.

Los Angeles has won five of six games and is 4-1 under Joe
Bryant, who replaced Henry Bibby as coach Aug. 16.

Holdsclaw scored 20 points on 9-of-12 shooting from the floor.
Lisa Leslie, who played the final 5:58 with five personal fouls,
scored 17 and grabbed 12 rebounds.

"Coach wanted me to run the pick and roll and get to the
basket," the 6-foot-2 Holdsclaw said of her game-winning shot over
6-6 Chantelle Anderson. Holdsclaw hit her final five shots as Los
Angeles made 11 of its final 12.

"Either I would find an open shot or help create for someone
else," Holdsclaw said.

San Antonio completed its season at a franchise-worst 7-27. The
Silver Stars also matched a franchise record with their ninth
straight loss. It's their second straight season with less than 10
wins and third straight with less than 15.

"That was a glimpse of our season in a nutshell," San Antonio
coach Dan Hughes said. "The effort was outstanding. By and large,
this team competed all year.

"Chamique Holdsclaw is tough and she made some big plays to
complement what they were doing."

Reserve La Toya Thomas led the Silver Stars with 14 points, 12
in the first half.

The Silver Stars led by 13 points with 12:14 remaining. The
Sparks failed to score in the opening 4:07 of the second half and
couldn't hit a shot from the floor for 5:57 after halftime.

But Los Angeles went on a 25-11 run and took a 63-62 lead with
3:11 remaining. San Antonio regained the lead on Dalma Ivanyi's
3-point shot to make it 67-65.

Leslie hit a pair of free throws to tie the game with 1:52 to
go.

"The key thing for us was to have a killer instinct and learn
how to win these games by playing together," Leslie said. "We
played through our offense as opposed to trying to go one on one,
and it was very successful for us."

Holdsclaw blocked Wendy Palmer-Daniel's shot underneath the
basket with 40 seconds left and hit the winner the next trip down
the floor. Holdsclaw picked up a loose ball and hit a free throw
with .1 seconds remaining for the final point.
